{"id":"2110.14767","submitter":"Amir Weiss","authors":"Amir Weiss, Toros Arikan, Hari Vishnu, Grant B. Deane, Andrew C.\n  Singer, and Gregory W. Wornell","title":"A Semi-Blind Method for Localization of Underwater Acoustic Sources","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1109/TSP.2022.3173731","report-no":null,"categories":"eess.SP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Underwater acoustic localization has traditionally been challenging due to\nthe presence of unknown environmental structure and dynamic conditions. The\nproblem is richer still when such structure includes occlusion, which causes\nthe loss of line-of-sight (LOS) between the acoustic source and the receivers,\non which many of the existing localization algorithms rely. We develop a\nsemi-blind passive localization method capable of accurately estimating the\nsource's position even in the possible absence of LOS between the source and\nall receivers. Based on typically-available prior knowledge of the water\nsurface and bottom, we derive a closed-form expression for the optimal\nestimator under a multi-ray propagation model, which is suitable for\nshallow-water environments and high-frequency signals. By exploiting a\ncomputationally efficient form of this estimator, our methodology makes\ncomparatively high-resolution localization feasible. We also derive the\nCram\\'er-Rao bound for this model, which can be used to guide the placement of\ncollections of receivers so as to optimize localization accuracy. The method\nimproves a balance of accuracy and robustness to environmental model mismatch,\nrelative to existing localization methods that are useful in similar settings.\nThe method is validated with simulations and water tank experiments.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 27 Oct 2021 20:58:26 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 2 Feb 2023 20:07:07 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-06"}
